content.text:
Triangle $ABC$ is written $\triangle ABC$. Its vertices are $A$, $B$, $C$; 
its sides are $\overline{AB}$, $\overline{BC}$, $\overline{CA}$; its 
angles are $\angle A$, $\angle B$, $\angle C$.

content.content:
Given $\triangle ABC$. Through vertex $C$, draw line $\ell$ parallel to 
$\overline{AB}$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=1.2]
 (A) at (0,0);
 (B) at (4,0);
 (C) at (1.5,2);

 (A) – (B) – (C) – cycle;
 (-0.5,2) – (4.5,2);

 at (A) {$A$};
 at (B) {$B$};
 at (C) {$C$};

 at (0.35,0.25) { $1$};
 at (3.6,0.25) { $2$};
 at (1.5,1.65) { $3$};
 at (0.7,2.2) { $4$};
 at (2.3,2.2) { $5$};

 at (4.5,2) {$\ell$};
tikzpicture
center

Since $\ell \parallel \overline{AB}$:

- $\angle 4 \cong \angle 1$ (alternate interior angles)

- $\angle 5 \cong \angle 2$ (alternate interior angles)

Angles $4$, $3$, and $5$ form a straight angle, so:
\[
 m\angle 4 + m\angle 3 + m\angle 5 = 180°
\]

Substituting:
\[
 m\angle 1 + m\angle 3 + m\angle 2 = 180°
\]
